As a team that has broken barriers, it's fun to celebrate and encourage the diversity growing within hockey.  @predsnhl players like @jtootoo22 , @lukeprokop_ , etc being the first in the NHL to represent their people/community/culture, etc. is a pretty special thing for a young(ish) franchise in such an old and historic sport that is composed of so many people beyond our borders (literally and metaphorically). I, along with many other decent and open minded people, enjoy seeing that reflected both on ice and in special game day nods which helps reflect the composition of our community we live in and the diversity of our fans, friends, and family in the arena sitting beside us cheering them on. Games are a little more happy with folks like @predxican98 in the stands. It's unfortunate you don't share the same values and cultural appreciations. One of the ways to mitigate bigotry or prejudices and all-around malicious attitudes is to educate and inform people. Which, the Preds have done from day one. whether that's Pete/Terry teaching "prednecks" about hockey in the South or having a Hispanic Heritage night... education has value; people often fear what they don't understand and we all know fear leads to hate and hate leads to suffering. 
As the saying goes: "I can only explain it to you, but I can't understand it for you."

It’s weird that we single groups out all the time if it’s already for everyone. If it’s for everyone we can say “it’s for everyone” and leave it at that. Stop dividing fans by skin color, ethnicity, sexual preference. It’s a systemic division that tricks the simple minded into thinking it’s inclusion.

That's the goal, right? But that's not really possible or realistic until fundamentals and basic rights are foundationally and unquestionably equal. So until then, education and information are a resource and tool to help get there. Along side that is "desensitization" or more accurately familiarization and expoosure to things that are foreign, different, opposing ideas/beliefs, etc . Understanding others or at least attempting to creates a more palatable world. In some cases it may reinforce your own beliefs. So, all the more reason to find a reason to enjoy something and welcome the extra with an open mind and see it as a learning and growth opportunity. So tonight, watch some hockey and learn something about a people which makes up roughly 11% of our community.
